COLIN QUINN: Thanks.

00:35:52.760 --> 00:35:55.390
AUDIENCE: I went to the
Minetta Lane Theater.

00:35:55.390 --> 00:35:58.146
But my question for you is--

00:35:58.146 --> 00:35:59.520
you touched on
this a little bit.

00:35:59.520 --> 00:36:02.740
But there is a
lot of controversy

00:36:02.740 --> 00:36:05.350
around what some
comedians talk about,

00:36:05.350 --> 00:36:09.010
like certain topics
having to be off limits,

00:36:09.010 --> 00:36:13.670
like racial jokes or sexuality
jokes, and things like that.

00:36:13.670 --> 00:36:15.760
And I struggle with
that personally,

00:36:15.760 --> 00:36:18.310
because some of the jokes,
I do find funny, personally.

00:36:18.310 --> 00:36:20.650
So I have that struggle myself.

00:36:20.650 --> 00:36:22.700
I'm like, oh, shoot, like
I don't want to laugh,

00:36:22.700 --> 00:36:25.480
but it's making me laugh.

00:36:25.480 --> 00:36:27.490
What is your
perspective on that?

00:36:27.490 --> 00:36:29.590
Should some of these
jokes be off limits?

00:36:29.590 --> 00:36:32.770
And that internal struggle
that some people may have,

00:36:32.770 --> 00:36:36.280
like is it warranted?

00:36:36.280 --> 00:36:37.750
Should we move past it?

00:36:37.750 --> 00:36:41.070
Because I don't necessarily
think that everyone's bigoted,

00:36:41.070 --> 00:36:44.720
but I understand the rationale
for not having these jokes.

00:36:44.720 --> 00:36:47.500
So it's sort of a struggle
for me, personally.

00:36:47.500 --> 00:36:48.250
COLIN QUINN: Yeah.

00:36:48.250 --> 00:36:51.240
Well, that's-- yeah, I
mean, it's a good question,

00:36:51.240 --> 00:36:54.150
because everybody gets
offended by something.

00:36:54.150 --> 00:36:56.180
I always quote this
guy Jack Simmons,

00:36:56.180 --> 00:37:01.560
who was a comedian from
the '80s, where I'm from,

00:37:01.560 --> 00:37:03.720
the place where I came from.

00:37:03.720 --> 00:37:05.310
But he used to
always go onstage,

00:37:05.310 --> 00:37:06.930
and when people would moan,
he would go, come on, folks.

00:37:06.930 --> 00:37:07.770
It's comedy.

00:37:07.770 --> 00:37:09.360
Somebody has got to get hurt.

00:37:09.360 --> 00:37:10.440
And that's the thing.

00:37:10.440 --> 00:37:13.980
So we've just shifted
what's offensive now.

00:37:13.980 --> 00:37:17.046
So it's kind of like, there
are things that offend me.

00:37:17.046 --> 00:37:18.420
There are things
that offend you.

00:37:18.420 --> 00:37:21.030
And like I say in
the show, I say,

00:37:21.030 --> 00:37:23.340
since they've gotten
rid of ethnic humor

00:37:23.340 --> 00:37:26.810
from mainstream society, because
they felt it encourages racism,

00:37:26.810 --> 00:37:28.350
I go, that's proven.

00:37:28.350 --> 00:37:29.740
Racism is gone.

00:37:29.740 --> 00:37:31.654
So it was a great success.

00:37:31.654 --> 00:37:32.910
Do you know what I mean?

00:37:32.910 --> 00:37:37.440
I feel like there's too much
focus on stand-up material.

00:37:37.440 --> 00:37:41.520
Everything is--
stand-up is not nice.

00:37:41.520 --> 00:37:43.080
And sometimes people
say things that

00:37:43.080 --> 00:37:45.480
make me mad in
stand-up, all the time.

00:37:45.480 --> 00:37:49.380
But like you say, if you're
laughing, you shouldn't feel,

00:37:49.380 --> 00:37:52.320
ugh, why am I laughing at this?

00:37:52.320 --> 00:37:56.380
Like suddenly it makes
you into something that--

00:37:56.380 --> 00:37:58.590
there's just a-- there's no--

00:37:58.590 --> 00:37:59.700
what do they call it?

00:37:59.700 --> 00:38:03.060
Suspension of disbelief, which
is a term that always bugged

00:38:03.060 --> 00:38:06.020
me, because I think it supposed
to be a suspension of belief,

00:38:06.020 --> 00:38:08.200
and suspension of disbelief.

00:38:08.200 --> 00:38:09.000
But another time.

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:12.870
But anyway, the point is,
like when you're at a movie,

00:38:12.870 --> 00:38:15.110
you say, OK, I'm
going into this world.

00:38:15.110 --> 00:38:17.890
And stand-up, I know
it's not the same thing.

00:38:17.890 --> 00:38:20.880
There is a lot more
truth to stand-up.

00:38:20.880 --> 00:38:22.230
So it isn't all just jokes.

00:38:22.230 --> 00:38:22.730
I get it.

00:38:22.730 --> 00:38:25.200
But yeah, I don't feel--

00:38:25.200 --> 00:38:27.630
I feel like it's
going down a path

00:38:27.630 --> 00:38:31.380
that I can't imagine how there
will be jokes in five years,

00:38:31.380 --> 00:38:33.910
because if everything falls
under this standard of,

00:38:33.910 --> 00:38:34.800
you know what?

00:38:34.800 --> 00:38:37.480
That group of people,
that's a little bit off.

00:38:37.480 --> 00:38:40.560
I mean, you'll see it
now like in stand-up.

00:38:40.560 --> 00:38:45.780
Somebody will say any
name of any group,

00:38:45.780 --> 00:38:47.190
and people are like [GASPING].

00:38:47.190 --> 00:38:49.210
Just before they
even get to the joke.

00:38:49.210 --> 00:38:51.240
So it's like people say,
celebrate diversity.

00:38:51.240 --> 00:38:53.175
Just don't point out
anybody is different.

00:38:53.175 --> 00:38:54.690
Do you know what I mean?

00:38:54.690 --> 00:38:57.520
Well, there's got
to be at some point,

00:38:57.520 --> 00:39:00.400
someone's got to come with
a little clear point of what

00:39:00.400 --> 00:39:00.900
it is.

00:39:00.900 --> 00:39:02.550
It's just people marking down.

00:39:02.550 --> 00:39:04.025
OK, that's an 8.5.

00:39:04.025 --> 00:39:05.400
We're just going
to have to start

00:39:05.400 --> 00:39:09.450
doing it based on, out of 10,
how offensive is that joke?

00:39:09.450 --> 00:39:11.250
And how wrong am
I for enjoying it?

00:39:11.250 --> 00:39:11.900
2.4.

00:39:11.900 --> 00:39:12.900
Do you know what I mean?

00:39:12.900 --> 00:39:15.540
Because stand-up gets to be in
this weird place where it will

00:39:15.540 --> 00:39:16.500
be--

00:39:16.500 --> 00:39:19.785
we might as well be in
the 1950s at a glee club,

00:39:19.785 --> 00:39:21.660
where you're just like
everything's positive.

00:39:21.660 --> 00:39:23.451
I mean, in stand-up,
everything's negative.

00:39:23.451 --> 00:39:24.640
That's what it's about.

00:39:24.640 --> 00:39:25.350
So I don't know.

00:39:25.350 --> 00:39:26.550
I don't know.

00:39:26.550 --> 00:39:28.740
But I don't-- personally,
I don't like it.

00:39:28.740 --> 00:39:29.730
I'll say that.

00:39:29.730 --> 00:39:31.669
I don't think it's
good for stand-up.

00:39:31.669 --> 00:39:32.460
And I don't think--

00:39:32.460 --> 00:39:35.579
I think most stand-ups agree
with me that it's weird.

00:39:35.579 --> 00:39:37.620
And you don't want it to
become the kind of thing

00:39:37.620 --> 00:39:40.210
where stand-up is just
motivational speaking,

00:39:40.210 --> 00:39:44.670
or people are just lecturing the
audience, which happens a lot,

00:39:44.670 --> 00:39:45.960
sometimes I feel like.

00:39:45.960 --> 00:39:48.240
Where suddenly it was like,
now, this is what goes on.

00:39:48.240 --> 00:39:50.580
And you're like, OK, we're
within the parameters.

00:39:50.580 --> 00:39:53.334
Like, stand-up punches
down sometimes.

00:39:53.334 --> 00:39:54.250
It doesn't just punch.

00:39:54.250 --> 00:39:56.208
People are like, stand-up
shouldn't punch down.

00:39:56.208 --> 00:39:56.910
Yeah, it should.

00:39:56.910 --> 00:39:57.660
It punches up.

00:39:57.660 --> 00:39:58.470
It punches down.

00:39:58.470 --> 00:40:00.300
It elbows you in the
side of the face.

00:40:00.300 --> 00:40:01.470
It's dirty.

00:40:01.470 --> 00:40:02.240
Stand-up is wrong.

00:40:02.240 --> 00:40:03.240
Do you know what I mean?

00:40:03.240 --> 00:40:05.130
So that's the other
part of it that's

00:40:05.130 --> 00:40:07.094
kind of getting
into a weird area.

00:40:07.094 --> 00:40:09.510
I realize that I've spent the
last eight minutes answering

00:40:09.510 --> 00:40:10.093
this question.

00:40:10.093 --> 00:40:13.995
And don't think I'm not
aware that I've said nothing.

00:40:17.780 --> 00:40:20.490
Such are the times we live in.

00:40:23.437 --> 00:40:24.270
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:40:24.270 --> 00:40:25.103
COLIN QUINN: Thanks.

00:40:28.482 --> 00:40:30.690
AUDIENCE: Can you speak in
your Northern Irish accent

00:40:30.690 --> 00:40:32.274
for the next like--
until you're done?

00:40:32.274 --> 00:40:33.731
COLIN QUINN: For
the next how long?

00:40:33.731 --> 00:40:34.527
AUDIENCE: What?

00:40:34.527 --> 00:40:35.610
COLIN QUINN: For how long?

00:40:35.610 --> 00:40:37.140
AUDIENCE: Just until
we're done, I guess.

00:40:37.140 --> 00:40:38.556
Or until someone
tells you, please

00:40:38.556 --> 00:40:41.330
don't speak in an Irish accent,
because I don't understand you.

00:40:41.330 --> 00:40:42.650
COLIN QUINN: (IRISH
ACCENT) Yes, I will.

00:40:42.650 --> 00:40:43.500
I'll do it like that.

00:40:43.500 --> 00:40:43.940
AUDIENCE: Awesome.

00:40:43.940 --> 00:40:44.380
Thank you.

00:40:44.380 --> 00:40:46.950
COLIN QUINN: (IRISH ACCENT) And
I'll tell you something else.

00:40:46.950 --> 00:40:48.622
I hope Irish people
don't see it,

00:40:48.622 --> 00:40:50.080
because they might
think it stinks.

00:40:52.900 --> 00:40:54.240
DAVID WINDMUELLER: OK.

00:40:54.240 --> 00:40:56.573
AUDIENCE: I'll give you the
out, and answer this however

00:40:56.573 --> 00:40:58.867
you feel most comfortable.

00:40:58.867 --> 00:41:01.200
So when you talk about the
evolution of stand-up comedy,

00:41:01.200 --> 00:41:03.510
especially political
commentary, like thinking back

00:41:03.510 --> 00:41:10.390
to Lenny Bruce, Bill Hicks,
where we are now, is it easier?

00:41:10.390 --> 00:41:11.220
Is it harder?

00:41:11.220 --> 00:41:14.130
Is it just the exact
same situation?

00:41:14.130 --> 00:41:17.130
Are we in a different place?

00:41:17.130 --> 00:41:18.360
Have audiences evolved?

00:41:18.360 --> 00:41:19.890
Have comedians evolved?

00:41:19.890 --> 00:41:22.800
Or are we just stuck on a loop?

00:41:22.800 --> 00:41:24.900
COLIN QUINN: From
those days, you mean?

00:41:24.900 --> 00:41:27.330
Yeah, I mean, this is going
to be another long-winded one.

00:41:27.330 --> 00:41:29.410
I'm just warning
you ahead of time.

00:41:29.410 --> 00:41:32.670
I can sense I'm going
to be rambling again.

00:41:32.670 --> 00:41:34.204
But it's evolved.

00:41:34.204 --> 00:41:36.120
Here's how you know it's
going to be too long.

00:41:36.120 --> 00:41:40.200
It's evolved and devolved
at the same time.

00:41:40.200 --> 00:41:42.380
I really am a big mouth.

00:41:42.380 --> 00:41:45.330
But it's evolved
in that people--

00:41:45.330 --> 00:41:47.160
like when I was doing
comedy in the '80s,

00:41:47.160 --> 00:41:50.079
people would just get away
with murder, just cheap things.

00:41:50.079 --> 00:41:51.620
You'd be like, that's
not even funny.

00:41:51.620 --> 00:41:55.270
It's just the shock or
whatever of the audience.

00:41:55.270 --> 00:41:58.310
So now people are listening
more, which is good.

00:41:58.310 --> 00:42:01.900
But it's devolved in the
sense that everybody--

00:42:01.900 --> 00:42:04.090
I feel like there's
almost like a film,

00:42:04.090 --> 00:42:06.820
like a fake film
over everything.

00:42:06.820 --> 00:42:09.880
So when people speak,
it's almost like we

00:42:09.880 --> 00:42:13.570
all agree like, OK,
you're saying this exists

00:42:13.570 --> 00:42:15.140
that we know doesn't exist.

00:42:15.140 --> 00:42:17.602
And then the jokes will
come within this fake world

00:42:17.602 --> 00:42:18.185
we've created.

00:42:21.532 --> 00:42:22.990
It wasn't as long
as the other one.

00:42:22.990 --> 00:42:25.344
But it was just as
hard to figure out.

00:42:25.344 --> 00:42:26.760
I don't even know
what I'm saying.

00:42:26.760 --> 00:42:27.926
But do you know what I mean?

00:42:27.926 --> 00:42:30.560
I just feel like there's
something very fake going on,

00:42:30.560 --> 00:42:32.885
and it's infected
stand-up, too, you know?

00:42:32.885 --> 00:42:35.199
Where people are like,
it should be appropriate.

00:42:35.199 --> 00:42:36.490
Stand-up should be appropriate.

00:42:36.490 --> 00:42:38.180
It's like, no, the
whole point of stand-up

00:42:38.180 --> 00:42:39.240
is it's not appropriate.

00:42:39.240 --> 00:42:40.880
It's kind of--

00:42:40.880 --> 00:42:43.910
I mean, part of the
fun of a stand-up show

00:42:43.910 --> 00:42:45.500
is you're like, oh, my god.

00:42:45.500 --> 00:42:46.220
Come on, man.

00:42:46.220 --> 00:42:47.640
That's too much.

00:42:47.640 --> 00:42:48.830
Do you know what I mean?

00:42:48.830 --> 00:42:51.170
And now it's sort of
like that too much

00:42:51.170 --> 00:42:53.030
is based on something fake.

00:42:53.030 --> 00:42:55.530
So people are almost
forcing themselves.

00:42:55.530 --> 00:42:58.190
I'm single-handedly bringing
down the stand-up industry

00:42:58.190 --> 00:42:59.010
right now.

00:42:59.010 --> 00:43:00.335
You're going to go, I don't
want to go to a comedy club

00:43:00.335 --> 00:43:02.100
if it sucks as bad as he says.

00:43:02.100 --> 00:43:03.560
But I'm saying there's still
a lot of great stand-up

00:43:03.560 --> 00:43:04.180
out there.

00:43:04.180 --> 00:43:05.971
Hey, there's still a
lot of great stand-up.

00:43:05.971 --> 00:43:07.670
But I mean, there's something.

00:43:07.670 --> 00:43:09.930
When it comes to
politics or whatever,

00:43:09.930 --> 00:43:14.800
there's just a general
feeling of appropriate that's

00:43:14.800 --> 00:43:16.580
not what stand-up is to me.

00:43:16.580 --> 00:43:17.415
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:43:17.415 --> 00:43:18.150
COLIN QUINN: Thanks.

00:43:18.150 --> 00:43:19.358
DAVID WINDMUELLER: All right.

00:43:19.358 --> 00:43:20.780
Well, thank you, Colin Quinn.

00:43:20.780 --> 00:43:22.160
"Red State Blue State."

00:43:22.160 --> 00:43:22.993
COLIN QUINN: Thanks.

